## When to use
Use this skill when you need detailed information about running processes on your Linux system, such as identifying resource usage or tracking down problematic processes.

## Approach
Utilize the `ps` command with various options to filter and display process information effectively. Combine it with other commands like `grep`, `sort`, and `awk` for more specific analysis. For instance, you can use `shell_exec` in KDEV to run complex `ps` commands to gather detailed metrics about processes.

## Example
To find the top 10 CPU-consuming processes on a Linux system, use:
```shell
ps -eo pid,%cpu,cmd --sort=-%cpu | head -n 11
```
You can achieve this in KDEV by executing:
```python
result = shell_exec("ps -eo pid,%cpu,cmd --sort=-%cpu | head -n 11")
print(result)
```

## Pitfalls
Be cautious of using `ps` with different shells or environments as the output format may vary. Ensure you are in a consistent environment when parsing the results. Also, be mindful that `ps` by default shows processes for the current user; use `-u <username>` to include other users if necessary.